revision.text:
{{Location map|Japan Mapplot|coordinates={{Coord|33.806823|135.64888}}|caption=Kii Road (around the Daitoyama Mountains area)|width=256}} '''Kii Road''' ({{ill|Kii Road|ja|紀伊路|12=draft}}, formerly also known as '''Kiro'''〈{{ill|Kiro|ja|紀路|12=draft}}〉) is one of the pilgrimage routes of the {{ill|Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|12=draft}} and a branch of the {{ill|Kumano Kodo|ja|熊野古道|12=draft}}.
It begins at the mouth of the {{ill|Yodogawa|ja|淀川|12=draft}} at {{ill|Watanabetsu|ja|渡辺津|12=draft}} (in {{ill|Settsu Province|ja|摂津国|12=draft}}), heading straight south, passing through {{ill|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|12=draft}}, crossing the {{ill|Onoyama Pass|ja|雄ノ山峠|12=draft}}, entering {{ill|Kii Province|ja|紀伊国|12=draft}}, and from {{ill|Tanabe City|ja|田辺市|12=draft}} (displayed as Kii Tanabe) proceeding east along the peripheral area of the {{ill|Daitoyama Mountains|ja|大塔山地|12=draft}} until reaching {{ill|Kumano Hongū Taisha|ja|熊野本宮大社|12=draft}}, from which routes lead to both {{ill|Kumano Hayatama Taisha|ja|熊野速玉大社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kumano Nachi Taisha|ja|熊野那智大社|12=draft}}.
Until the early modern period, the section east of Kii Tanabe was known as the '''Nakahechi''' ({{ill|Nakahechi|ja|中辺路|12=draft}}) (see [[#中辺路|later description]]), but this article deals with the route as a whole.
== Overview == [[File:Map Kumano Kodo (ja).png|thumb|right|300px|Map of the Kumano Kodo. The light blue and yellow lines indicate the Kii Road]] The Kii Road is a pilgrimage route linking the {{ill|Kinai|ja|畿内|12=draft}} region with the Kumano Sanzan. Among the Kumano Kodo routes, it is one of the oldest known—together with the {{ill|Ise Road|ja|伊勢路|12=draft}}—as celebrated in the {{ill|Ryōjin Hisho|ja|梁塵秘抄|12=draft}}. However, due to the constraints imposed by the {{ill|Izumi Mountains|ja|和泉山脈|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Kongō Range|ja|葛城山脈|12=draft}} in Settsu and Izumi, and by the {{ill|Kii Mountains|ja|紀伊山地|12=draft}} and its originating rivers in Kii Province, the route was far from easy.
Despite these difficulties, from the 7th century onward the Kii Road was formally recognized as a pilgrimage route to the Kumano Sanzan, witnessing a flourishing of pilgrimages by the retired emperors of {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都|12=draft}} and the aristocracy. Moreover, during the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安|12=draft}} to the early {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉|12=draft}}—when medieval Kumano pilgrimages were undertaken principally on foot and included visits to the {{ill|Kujūkuni Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|12=draft}}—ascetic practitioners (【修験者】) led the way by organizing the routes and instructing in pilgrimage rituals, thus endowing the arduous journey with profound religious significance.
Medieval Kumano pilgrimages eventually came to an end when the institutions that had been the main drivers of these journeys—the retired emperors and the powerful Kumano Betto families who had long governed the Kumano Sanzan with imperial backing—declined following the 【Jōkyū War】. Thereafter, as the principal pilgrims shifted to eastern warriors and influential farmers, the character of the Kii Road changed; it gradually lost its status as the main route and was eventually incorporated into the network of the {{ill|Nishi no Sanjūsho Pilgrimage Routes|ja|西国三十三所|12=draft}}. Although Kumano pilgrimages did not disappear entirely, the elaborate rituals of the medieval period were lost, and alternative branch routes were established to bypass particularly difficult sections. In the regions of Settsu and Izumi, the Kii Road was also known as the {{ill|Kumano Kaidō|ja|熊野街道|1=Kumano Kaidō|12=draft}}, serving as a main thoroughfare for local residents and playing significant political and economic roles. In modern times, when national road networks were established, the Kii Road’s original route was often followed.
The Kii Road, which set out from Watanabetsu at the mouth of the {{ill|Yodogawa|ja|淀川|12=draft}} in Settsu Province, runs nearly parallel to the {{ill|Kishu Kaidō|ja|紀州街道|12=draft}} along a line of spring water emerging from the foothills of the Izumi Hills, before turning over the hills near what is now {{ill|Hannan City|ja|阪南市|12=draft}}. It then converges with the similarly re-routed Kishu Kaidō at the {{ill|Onoyama Pass|ja|雄ノ山峠|12=draft}}, entering Kii Province. Crossing the {{ill|Central Tectonic Line|ja|中央構造線|12=draft}} to the south at the Kino River, the terrain derived from the Kii Mountains continues with a series of rivers that originate there—the {{ill|Kino River|ja|紀ノ川|12=draft}}, {{ill|Arita River|ja|有田川|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Hidaka River|ja|日高川|12=draft}}—until reaching Tanabe. From Tanabe the road heads east; after following the valley of the {{ill|Iwatagawa|ja|岩田川|12=draft}} and turning over the hills at {{ill|Takijiri|ja|滝尻王子|12=draft}}, it continues along the northern edge of the {{ill|Daitoyama Mountain Range|ja|大塔山系|12=draft}} to finally arrive at {{ill|Kumano Hongū Taisha|ja|熊野本宮大社|12=draft}}, from which routes extend for the subsequent pilgrimage to {{ill|Kumano Hayatama Taisha|ja|熊野速玉大社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kumano Nachi Taisha|ja|熊野那智大社|12=draft}}.
As mentioned above, the Kii Road was not only a path of faith but also a vital route for daily life, and it continued to be used into modern times. However, as easier routes capable of accommodating automobile traffic were developed, many sections that once ran along settlements lost their original form or ceased to exist as proper roads. In 1978 ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft}} 53), the {{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs|ja|文化庁|12=draft}} selected the Kumano Pilgrimage Routes in {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}} and {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|12=draft}}, namely the Kii Road, as one of the "100 Selected Historical Routes". This prompted comprehensive investigations into the route and its history. As a result, the portion of the Kii Road east of Tanabe—well preserved in the area of Nakahechi in Tanabe City—has been restored and improved, enabling at least a partial retracing of the original pilgrimage path.
