{{Location map|Japan Mapplot|coordinates={{Coord|33.806823|135.64888}}|caption=Kii Road (around the Daitoyama Mountains area)|width=256}} '''Kii Road''' ({{ill|Kii Road|ja|紀伊路|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kii Road|qq=}}, formerly also known as '''Kiro'''〈{{ill|Kiro|ja|紀路|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiro|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}〉) is one of the pilgrimage routes of the {{ill|Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} and a branch of the [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodo]].
It begins at the mouth of the [[:en:Yodo River|Yodogawa]] at {{ill|Watanabetsu|ja|渡辺津|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watanabetsu|qq=}} (in [[:en:Settsu Province|Settsu Province]]), heading straight south, passing through [[:en:Izumi Province|Izumi Province]], crossing the {{ill|Onoyama Pass|ja|雄ノ山峠|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onoyama Pass|qq=}}, entering [[:en:Kii Province|Kii Province]], and from [[:en:Tanabe, Wakayama|Tanabe City]] (displayed as Kii Tanabe) proceeding east along the peripheral area of the {{ill|Daitoyama Mountains|ja|大塔山地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daitoyama Mountains|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} until reaching [[:en:Kumano Hongū Taisha|Kumano Hongū Taisha]], from which routes lead to both [[:en:Kumano Hayatama Taisha|Kumano Hayatama Taisha]] and [[:en:Kumano Nachi Taisha|Kumano Nachi Taisha]].
Until the early modern period, the section east of Kii Tanabe was known as the '''Nakahechi''' ({{ill|Nakahechi|ja|中辺路|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakahechi|qq=}}) (see [[#中辺路|later description]]), but this article deals with the route as a whole.
